column168: When the Wheeling and Lake Erie Brewster Yard Car Inspector were walking the yard tracks, the noticed tank car UTLX 950388 was hissing from the top of the car. column168: during offloading operations, it was discovered that approximately 5 liquid gallons of a UN3266 Corrosive liquid NOS. ( Hydro-Guard Solution ) was released to the wooden freight trailer floor (approx 4.5 gallons) and adjacent concrete parking lot (approx 1/2 gallon) from a 330 gallon poly caged tote resulting from an apparently defective seal on the discharge valve. An environmental contractor was dispatched and transferred the remaining product into a replacement tote. the replacement tote was staged on site pending the shipper's disposition. The contractor utilized a citric acid solution and granular absorbents to clean the impacted areas. All wastes were collected, containerized, labelled and left on site for pending disposal.

During offloading operations, it was discovered that approximately 2 liquid cups of a UN1993 Flammable Liquid NOS ( Entegrate PI 7205 ) was released from a 330 gallon stainless steel tote in the rear of a freight trailer resulting from an apparently loose cap. The spill was contained to the top of the tote only and the minimal release evaporated prior to completion of the contractor's response. No drains, soils or waterways were impacted by this release. An environmental contractor was dispatched and discovered that the top tote cap was loose (less that hand tight) which resulted in the release. The contractor inspected the cap, adjusted the seal and gasket and re-affixed the cap. The contractor preformed a slosh test and no further release was detected. No wastes were generated since the released product evaporated.

column58: Fusible Pressure Relief Device or Element
column168: On February 01, 2016 personnel in the CSXT Hopewell yard discovered TILX 135758, a loaded tank car of Molten Sulfur leaking from the top of the car.     The car was isolated and OXBOW, CHEMTREC, VA EOC and NRC were notified. CHEMTREC report # 2016-02-01-0020.     HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that the rupture disk assembly was less than tool tight. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Cristy Dean Phone # 281-907-9255.    The rupture disk assembly was fixed and the car released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.     NAR Cause Code: 425 - Non Reclosing Pressure Relief Device    5 (5 + 1 + 0) X (2 + 0) = 60 NARRI
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 02/01/16 at 1740 hours CSXT yard personnel at the CSXT Gentilly Yard terminal located at 6701 Almonaster Ave, New Orleans, LA discovered GATX29815, a residue tank car of Cyclohexane, that was actively leaking from the vapor line valve stem nut. The car was isolated and the shipper, Fibrant LLC, was notified. United States Environmental Services, CSX Hazmat response contractor, responded and discovered that the vapor line valve nut was loose causing the vapor release. USES tightened the nut securing the leak.  The issue was communicated to the shipper The shipper will dispatch a certified mobile repair company to repair the valve and conduct a pressure test prior to the car being released.       NAR Cause Code: 379  Air Inlet Vapor Valve/ Valve Body-other    2(5+1+1) x (2+4) = 84 NARRI     New Orleans, LA  02/01/16  GATX29815-Cyclohexane
column169: No additional comments.

A vacuum box containing a shipment of hazardous waste was parked in the ten day yard of the intermediate truck transfer facility.  During a routine yard check, a small amount of liquid was noticed to be leaking from the rear door.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up the spilled material from the concrete.  The door was tightened and the leak stopped.  The box then continued to the intended disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The box was loaded when the outside temperature was cold and the material warmed up with the heat of the day.  This, combined with the rear door of the box not being completely tightened caused the leak.  The driver who picked up the box was cautioned about not insuring the box was tight.

column42: CARBON DIOXIDE, SOLID OR DRY ICE
column168: In the process of loading  freight shipment at air side AWB96862721 on AA Flight1096 ORDMCO on 2/2/2016, gate crew noticed a carton covered with frost. employees years of experience told him that items in this condition is usually a trigger that the shipment could contain Dry Ice. Shipment was not loaded and Cargo was notified. Cargo representative arrived at the gate. opened the carton and there was indeed Dry Ice inside the carton. When the shipment was tendered to Cargo the carton and all the supporting documents gave no indication that this was a Dangerous Goods. There was no markings or labels on the box or documentation on the air waybill indicating dry ice at the time of acceptance. There was no frost on the carton at time of acceptance. Gate crew discovered the undeclared dangerous goods because the box frosted up. Cartoon was brought back to cargo and shipper AIT WORLDWIDE LOGISTIC INC contacted. AA internal incident report was completed and local FAA office notify.
column169: For this particular shipper all receving agents will be paying special attention to their freight looking for all possible trigger especially shipment with the word gel pack to make sure there is no undecalred dangerous goods.

column168: During dock operations, an apparent forklift accident resulting the release of approximately 1 liquid gallon of a UN1824 Sodium Hydroxide Solution (M1801 Mainline Cleaner) from a fiberboard box containing 4-1 gallon plastic bottles to the concrete dock floor only. Terminal personnel applied granular absorbents and soda ash to the impacted area. All wastes were collected, containerized and staged on site for pending disposal.

during offloading operations, it was discovered that 2-330 gallon poly caged totes were apparently punctured due to a reported forklift accident resulting in the release of approximately 1/2 liquid gallon on a UN2693 Aqueous Bilsulite Solution ( BL-126). The release was confined to the tot and side body of the tote. No drains, soils or waterways were impacted by the releases. An environmental contractor was dispatched and transferred the product into field supplied replacement totes. The damaged totes were cut up, containerized and taken by the contractor for profiling and disposal.

column168: On February 3rd, 2016 at 1008 hours, personnel in the CSXT Frontier Yard were notified by FRA + NYS-DOT HazMat Inspectors that PROX 98365 a loaded UN1075, LPG (Propane) tank car was emitted vapors from the vapor line valve and secondary securement plug. The car was isolated and the shipper Plains Midstream Canada ULC was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2016-02-03-00093, Ms. Sheena Brister. A CSXT emergency response contractor was dispatched, upon investigation PROX 98365 was found to have the vapor line valve open 1/8 turn and the secondary securement plug was less than tool tight, due to excess thread tape being rolled up on the threaded plug face, there by not allowing the plug to fully seat into the vapor line valve. The contractor closed the vapor line valve, cleaned off the excess thread tape, applied a new layer of thread tape and tool tightened the secondary securement plug properly.  Plain Midstream Canada ULC rep. Ms. Sheena Brister was notified situation found and the corrective action taken to secure the tank car. PROX 98365 was released for dispo.     Cause Code: 136 (5 points)  NARRI: 5x(5+5+0)x(2+0) = 100

column168: A cargo tanker of UN1203 Gasoline was making a delivery to the Circle K gas station in Copley, OH. The driver finished filling the UN1203 87 Regular gasoline into the underground storage tank (UST) and went to fill the 93 premium portion of the UST. It was reported that the UST did not properly switch to the 93 premium. The 93 premium was deposited into the 87 regular tank, and caused a fuel overfill. Approximately 40 gallons of gasoline were released onto the pavement. The federal RQ for Benzene was met (RQ=10 pounds, 13 pounds released). A 40'x100' area of asphalt was impacted by the release. No soils were impacted. 1 drain was impacted. A nearby contractor responded to the incident. Absorbent boom was placed in the impacted drain and around the drains outfall. All impacted snow was shoveled into waste drums. The absorbent boom was replaced and will be picked up at a later date. The facility manager and Ohio EPA rep were satisfied with the cleanup.

A 406 ISO tanker hauling 45,000 lbs of UN1218 Isoprene was involved in a single vehicle rollover due to human error. The tanker veered to the right shoulder of the roadway and rolled over in a grassy median. The driver was injured and taken to the hospital for injuries sustained in the crash. I-10 was shut down for 5 hours due to this incident. The shell of the tanker was not damaged; however, 1 gallon of residual product released from a vent line and impacted the soil. Contractors were dispatched and the vehicle was up-righted without incident. No drains or waterways were impacted by this release

The material that had leaked was absorbed and also placed into the the salvage drum for disposal.
column169: As the leak appeared to be from a defective and not damaged drum that was rated for its lading, the recommendation is to continue close and daily visual inspections of containers held in storage prior to shipment.

column168: THE PACKAGE WAS IN THE CAGE, LOADER NOTICED PACKAGE WET. ONE 1-GALLON CONTAINER LEAKED BECAUSE OF LOOSE CAP. THERE WERE NO INNER SEALS.
THE PACKAGE WAS ON THE TOP SLIDE. THE SORTER NOTICED PACKAGE WAS WET BEFORE HE SORTED IN CAGE. ONE 1-GALLON CONTAINER LEAKED BECAUSE OF LOOSE CAP. THERE WERE NO INNER SEAL.

CALL WAS MADE TO THE DMP CAGE ABOUT A POSSIBLE LEAKING HAZMAT. DESIGNATED RESPONDER, WEARING FULL PPE AND USING A FULLY STOCKED HAZMAT CART, RESPONDED TO PD 10. PACKAGE WAS FOUND TO HAVE 1 SEAM OF THE BOX WET FROM THE INSIDE OUT. FOLLOWING ALL PROPER RESPONDER METHODS, PACKAGE WAS SECURED AND RETURNED TO THE DMP CAGE TO BE PROCESSED.
TOP OF CAN CRUSHED BREAKING CAP OFF CAN.

column168: RESPONDER WAS CALLED TO LEAKING PACKAGE ON SORT AISLE UPON INSPECTION NOTICED IT WAS A HAZMAT. BOTTLE PLASTIC OUTER SEAL FAILED TO OPERATE.
column169: PROPER PREPARATION PRIOR TO SHIPPING.

column168: RESPONDER CALLED TO BLUE SECONDARY TO RETRIEVE HAZARDOUS PACKAGE W/CORROSIVE 8 DIAMOND LABEL THAT HAD ONE CORNER WITH SMALL AMOUNT OF SATURATION ON BELT. RESPONDER CLEANED VERY SMALL AREA OF BLUE SECONDARY SLIDE THAT APPEARED DAMP AND BELT.

RESPONDER WAS DISPATCHED TO A LEAKING HAZMAT IN OUTBOUND 7 ON THE BULK LINE. UPON ARRIVAL, THE RESPONDER USED THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET, TO CONTAINERIZE AND CLEAN UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL. THE HAZMAT AND MATERIAL WAS THEN BROUGHT BACK TO THE HAZMAT DMP CAGE, FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. INFORMATION WAS THEN COLLECTED ON THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AND ENTERED INTO THE ETT SYSTEM. THE PROCESSED MATERIAL WAS THEN PLACED IN THE UNCONFIRMED DMP STORAGE AREA.

RESPONDER WAS DISPATCHED TO A LEAKING HAZMAT PACKAGE IN OB 5 ON THE BULK LINE. THE PROCESSED MATERIAL WAS THEN PLACED IN THE UNCONFIRMED DMP STORAGE AREA.

RESPONDER WAS SENT TO A LEAKING HAZMAT IN OVERGOODS. USING THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET, THE RESPONDER CONTAINERIZED THE WET HAZMAT AND BROUGHT IT BACK TO THE HAZMAT DMP CAGE, FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. THE HAZMAT WAS PROCESSED, INFORMATION WAS COLLECTED AND ENTERED INTO ETT. THE PROCESSED MATERIAL WAS STORED IN THE UNCONFIRMED DMP STORAGE AREA.
LEAKING HAZMAT PACKAGE DISCOVERED PD7. PICKED UP BY RESPONDER TRANSPORTED TO HAZMAT AREA AND PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP. CAP ON CUBETAINER WAS LOOSE AND LEAKING.

column168: EMPLOYEE FOUND LEAKING HAZMAT, DIDN'T TOUCH LEFT AREA NOTIFIED SUPERVISOR WHO CALLED FOR A RESPONDER WHO SHOWED UP IN FULL PPE AND FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE TO THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET AND CORRECTLY FOLLOWED THE STEPS TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL AND REMOVED ALL AFFECTED PACKAGES BACK TO THE PSC FOR PROCESSING. column25: Chevron Phillips Chemical Co. C/O Stolthaven Terminal
column168: CHVX 287002 was observed leaking from the bottom outlet valve at approximately 10:08 hours on Thursday, Feb 25, 2016. M&M Protection was notified to respond to the scene to inspect, repair and re-mediate the spill.  Upon arrival M&M found product dripping around the threads of the bottom outlet cap at a rate of one drop every 2-3 seconds.  M&M vented the pressure off of the car in order to remove the cap and inspect the valve.  Venting pressure slowed the leak considerably.  The gasket on the cap was intact but very brittle. There was also several small pieces of debris in the cap. M&M replace the gasket and reapplied the cap. They then opened the valve to try and clear any additional debris from the valve. The gasket held and did not show signs of leakage. However, after removing the cap again there was still product leaking from the valve.  At that time we notified the shipper, Stolthaven Terminal and Chevron Phillips. The shipper has elected to obtain an OTMA-1 to move the car back to stolt for off loading and then to a shop for inspection and repair.  At this time the bottom outlet cap is holding and the leak is contained.
column169: Chevron Phillips and Stolthaven terminal will be inspecting the valve to determine the cause of the leak.

column42: AMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S. OR POLYAMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S.
column168: A tractor trailer carrying 55 gallon poly drums of UN2735 corrosive amines reported a 1 gallon spill. The release was due to the drum falling off an open top trailer due to improper bracing for transport. No drains or waterways were impacted by this release. Contractors were dispatched for cleanup and over packing operations. All wastes were collected, containerized and taken by the contractor for profiling and disposal.

It was reported that the driver of a Landstar tractor trailer was delivering propane tanks to the Pinnacle Propane location in Sardis, MS. The driver dropped his trailer in the yard, and went to hook up to another trailer containing 200 propane tanks. When the driver connected his truck to the trailer, the nose of the trailer caught on fire. The driver disconnected and moved the truck. The fire was put out with fire extinguishers. After the fire was extinguished, everyone on site moved to a safe distance. Due to the heat of the fire, many of the propane tanks exploded.    An environmental contractor was dispatched in the morning to get photo documentation and determine the extent of the damage. It was reported that 50 tanks were completely empty, and 150 were damaged. The burn area was an 80' radius around the truck. The contractor offloaded the remaining debris in the trailer. A representative for Pinnacle Propane arrived onsite and instructed the contractor not to perform any cleanup, as Pinnacle Propane would manage it due to liability concerns.

column168: A LEAKING HAZMAT WAS CALLED IN AT 2115 BY SAM HERNANDEZ IN LOADING DOCK BAY 437. THE FIBERBOARD PACKAGE WAS UPRIGHT AND DIDN'T APPEAR TO BE DAMAGED BUT THERE WAS A PUDDLE OF LIQUID. THE PACKAGE CONTAINED 2 4-LITER BOTTLES OF SULFURIC ACID SOLUTION. THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS DUE TO LOOSE CAPS ON THE BOTTLES. I FOLLOWED MY DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET TO CLEAN UP SPILL AND BROUGHT PACKAGE BACK TO PSC FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.
RESPONDER WAS CALLED TO A WET PACKAGE, RESPONDED USING PROPER PPE

WHEN THEY OPENED TRAILER THEY SAW SOMETHING WET ON FLOOR AND WERE LOOKING AROUND AND SAW NOTHING DAMAGED IN AREA. FARTHER BACK THEY UNLOADED AND FOUND THE PACKAGE. IT COULD OF FALLEN WHEN THEY WERE LOADING IT AND THEY DID NOT REALIZE IT WAS LEAKING.
PACKAGE WAS LEAKING ON THE BELT BY THE PLATFORM. GLASS BOTTLE INSIDE OF PACKAGE WAS SHATTERED.

SUP CALLED AND NOTIFIED RESPONDER OF SPILL, DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET WAS USED, APPROPRIATE PPE WAS USED, PROPER CONTAINMENT PROCEDURES FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUID WAS FOLLOWED, PROPER DISPOSAL AND DECONTAMINATION PROCEDURES WERE TAKEN, UPON INSPECTION MULTIPLE LOOSE CAPS WERE IDENTIFIED AND ONE PLUG WAS DEFECTIVE.
column169: RECOMMEND USE OF GOOD PLUG AND ENSURE CAPS ARE PROPERLY TIGHTENED.

column168: On 2/5/16 at approximately 13:51 CST a BNSF mechanical employee reported a petroleum odor and became nauseous.  Kansas FD and Hazmat Team responded to the railyard and transported the employee to the Hospital.  The immediate area was isolated around the suspect car (HSRX 3141) which was near where the employee became ill.  BNSF Hazmat Responder and KCFD performed an entry to assess the area and recorded no abnormal air monitoring results using a 4-gas instrument and a PID.  It was noted that a slight petroleum odor was evident in the area.  KCFD demobilized from the scene after determining that no immediate risk was present in the area.  A BNSF Hazmat responder and the BNSF contractor conducted an additional assessment of the area including all Hazmat cars that were in the area.  The HSRX 3141 was not noticeably leaking at the time, however because the car had no vapor pressure as expected, it was determined to have the car set out for additional testing.  Once set out, the contractor added nitrogen pressure to the car and found a slight  audible leak at manway sealing area near the handle.  Two bolts were tightened and the leak stopped, pressure was increased to 20 psi and it was determined that no additional leaks were present.  All fittings and leak points were assessed.  The car was held for observation.  On 2/21/16, an odor was again observed from the area around the HSRX 3141.  The Hazmat Contractor returned, there was no direct evidence of a release and the car had 12 pounds of pressure on it.  The contractor opened the manway and determined that there was no gasket (lid or nozzle) in place.  A new gasket was installed and the car was resecured and monitored.  No additional odor was reported on 2/22/16.  Release estimates are based upon information provided by on-site responders.
column169: Shipper has been notified to address the pre-trip inspection process at the originating facility with those responsible for securing cars prior to transport.  The inspection should consist of evaluating and inspecting all fittings and closures on the railcar, regardless of whether or not the loading facility utilizes all fittings and closures.

column168: On February 9, 2016, at 2322 hours, a Transportation Manager at the CSXT Avon Terminal, Avon, Indiana reported that a derailment of three loaded hazmat tank cars and one loaded hopper car had occurred. Summit Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the Avon Terminal to perform damage assessment and inspection until CSXT Hazmat Managers could arrive. Summit found that XOMX 110056, a loaded tank car of UN1193 methyl ethyl ketone, was on its side and a small amount of product was leaking from the vacuum relief device. The vacuum relief device was sealed with a putty material and wrapped to avoid any additional leakage until it could be rerailed. The shipper, Exxonmobil, was notified via Chemtrec, report #2016-0209-00310. The shipper representative, Scott Murray, 832 625 3950   was notified of the situation found. Due to the derailment damage the load will  be transferred into a new tank car and returned to transportation. The XOMX 110056 will be cleaned and purged and await final disposition either to home shop for repairs on a flat car or scrapped.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 02/20/16 at 1843 hours it was reported at Sibert Yard (CSXT), located in Mobile, AL, that covered hopper car GACX470063, a residue hopper car of Ammonium Nitrate, to be leaking from the hatches on the bottom of the car. The shipper, Orica USA Inc, was notified. United States Environmental Services, CSXT response contractors, were dispatched to the scene. CSX Mechanical crews secured the secured the leak by closing the doors.  It was reported by CSX Mechanical that all of the bottom doors were partially open.  All doors were secured.  These actions were communicated to the shipper (Lyle Ewert 303 378 5722). The car was secured and released.    NAR Code unavailable due to being a hopper car        Mobile, AL  02/20/16  GACX470063  Ammonium Nitrate

column168: During unloading, one 330 gallon poly tote was punctured via forklift resulting in approximately 330 liquid gallons to be released to the trailer floor, asphalt parking lot, and adjacent soil. A contractor responded to conduct clean up operations under the supervision of the local FD.     The product has oxidized by the time an excavation of the soils had occurred.  All impacted material was containerized and is currently awaiting disposal.  Analytical results have indicated that the waste will be disposed of as non-hazardous.

column168: DRIVER WAS DISPATCHED TO DELIVER A LOAD OF GASOLINE TO DUNCAAN'S CORNER NEAR MONTICELLO, MS ON FEBRUARY 24, 2016. DRIVER IN TRAINING WAS ALSO ON BOARD. WHILE UNLOADING GASOLINE, A MALFUNCTION OCCURED IN THE PIPING SYSTEM BETWEEN TWO AGTS THAT WERE MANIFOLDED TOGETHER. THIS CAUSED AN OVERFILL OF ONE OF THE TANKS.  THE OVERFILL CONDITION CAUSED SOME GASOLINE TO SPRAY FROM THE VENT PIPE ON TOP OF THET ANK AND ON THE DELIVERY TRUCK BELOW. THE GASOLINE HIT THE HOOD OF THE TRUCK, VAPORIZED, AND WAS SUCKED INTO THE INTAKE OF THE DIESEL ENGINE CAUSING THE ENGINE TO RUN AWAY. A FIRE STARTED IN/UNDER THE ENGINE AND IN TURN CAUGHT THE CAB ON FIRE AND MELTED THE FRONT END OF THE TRAILER. THE TRUCK WAS DESTROYED BY THE FIRE AND THE TRAILER WAS DAMAGED BEYOND REPAIRS.    WHEN THE DRIVER NOTICED THE OVERFILL CONDITION, HE CLIMBED IN THE TRUCK TO ATTEMPT TO SWITCH THE ENGINE OFF, BUT WAS UNABLE TO SUCCESSFULLY SHUT THE ENGINE DOWN. AS HE SAW THE FIRE START, HE JUMPED OUT OF THE CAB ONTO THE CONCRETE DRIVE. THE IMPACT FROM THE JUMP BROKE HIS LEFT LEG BELOW THE KNEE AND FRACTURED HIS RIGHT HEEL. THE DRIVER IN TRAINING WAS ABLE TO ASSIST HIM TO SAFETY AND GET AWAY FROM THE TRUCK FIRE.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the transfer operation and while moving a pallet of drums using a forklift, one of the drums fell off the pallet, causing the ring to pop off resulting in a spill of 1 liquid pint. Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place the compromised container into a suitable salvage drum. In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.

column168: AFTER THE DRIVER OFF LOADED 1000 LG OF HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION TO THE UNH WATER TREATMENT PLANT, THE DRIVER FORGOT TO TIGHTEN THE DOME COVER DOWN. UPON LEAVING THE DELIVERY SITE, THE PRODUCT REMAINING IN THE TANK HAD SLOSHED AROUND AND STARTED TO LEAK OUT OF THE DOME COVER. THE DRIVER NOTICED HE WAS LEAVING A TRAIL AS HE DROVE UP THE ROAD A SHORT DISTANCE. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY STOPPED THE VEHICLE. STOPPED THE PRODUCT FROM LEAKING AND CALLED EMERGENCY PERSONNEL. DRIVER REPORTED THE SPILL TO COMPANY OFFICIALS. THE COMPANY OFFICIALS CONTACTED SPILLCENTER TO HELP CONTACT LOCAL AUTHORITIES AND A CLEAN UP CREW. SPILLCENTER CONTRACTED CYN ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT.
column169: H.O. BOUCHARD, INC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND REINFORCE SAFE HANDLING PROCEDURES AND DRIVER SAFETY TO ALL PERSONNEL. SUGGESTIONS WERE GIVEN TO TRY A DIFFERENT UNLOADING PROCEDURE WHEN A GRAVITY DROP IS NEEDED FOR SUCH A SMALL DELIVERY. SUGGESTION WAS TO LEAVE THE DOME COVER CLOSED AND OPEN THE AIR INLET VALVES THAT WOULD BE USED TO AIR PAD A TANK TO UNLOAD. THIS WILL KEEP THE DOME COVER CLOSED AND ALLOW ENOUGH AIR INSIDE THE TANK TO NOT CREATE A VACUUM AND POSSIBLY COLLAPSE THE TANK.

column168: EMPLOYEE BEN ASHLEY CAME TO DMP & ALERTED US TO A PACKAGE CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ON THE RED SECONDARY SLIDE WHICH WAS LEAKING WHITE VAPOR. MEANWHILE ALL OTHER EMPLOYEES EVACUATED THE AREA. WE ENTERED THE AREA (LESS THAN A MINUTE AFTER BEING ALERTED) TO INVESTIGATE & SAW VAPOR EXITING THE HAZMAT BOX. EMPLOYEE LILLIANN SMITH TURNED OFF ALL BELTS IN AREA WHILE EMPLOYEE NICK LODIEN CALLED UP THE CHAIN OF COMMAND. CONES WERE PLACED AT BOTTOM OF STAIRS TO KEEP ALL OTHER WORKERS OUT, & A 15 FT PERIMETER WAS MAINTAINED FOR RESPONDERS & MANAGEMENT INVESTIGATING THE SPILL. MEANWHILE EMPLOYEE COLTON STEWART-GARCIA CONTACTED AN OUTSIDE RESPONSE TEAM (O.R.T.) TO ADDRESS CLEAN UP OF THE SPILL. O.R.T. ARRIVED APPROX. 1.5HOURS LATER. ALL PERSONNEL WERE KEPT OUT OF AREA UNTIL ALL CLEAN UP WAS FINISHED BY O.R.T. & THEY SAID IT WAS CLEAR. O.R.T. PUT 20L STEEL DRUM IN 55 GALLON DRUM FILLED WITH VERMICULITE & PLACED NEAR OTHER FLAMMABLE HAZARDOUS WASTE BARRELS INSIDE BUILDING NEAR DMP AREA.

column168: DURING THE TRANSPORTATION OF THE MANIFESTED HAZARDOUS WASTE, THE DRIVER PULLED INTO A DOT WEIGH STATION FOR A LEVEL II INSPECTION. DRIVER EXITED THE TRACTOR AND STEPPED BACK FROM THE UNIT. DOT STAFF NOTED THE INITIATION OF DRIPPING MATERIAL FROM THE RUNOFF TUBING, AND ADVISED THE DRIVER. DRIVER REACHED THE MANWAY LID AND CHECKED ALL SEALS AND FOUND THE SAMPLE LID HAD AN IMPROPER SEAL. DRIVER SECURED THE SAMPLE LID UNTIL STC STAFF PERSONNEL ARRIVED ON SCENE TO ASSIST. DRIVER USED ABSORBENT PADDING AND SOCKS TO CONTAIN THE 0.5 GALLONS OF MATERIAL AND TO PICK UP THE MATERIAL. THE USED ABSORBENT MATERIALS WERE RETURNED TO THE SUMTER TRANSPORT COMPANY TEXARKANA HUB FACILITY. THERE WAS A DOCUMENTED PRE-TRANSPORTATION CHECK CONDUCTED BY A SUMTER TRANSPORT COMPANY FIELD SERVICES EMPLOYEE PRIOR TO THE TANKER LEAVING THE SHIPPER FACILITY. THAT INSPECTION DID NOT IDENTIFY THAT THE SAMPLE LID WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED.
column169: UPON THE INCIDENT NOTIFICATION TO SUMTER TRANSPORT COMPANY, ALL SUMTER TRANSPORT COMPANY TANKERS WERE STOPPED IN OPERATIONS, TAKEN INTO SERVICE FACILITIES, AND EACH MANWAY CAP WAS INSPECTED AND SECURED BEFORE PLACING THE TANKERS BACK IN SERVICE. SUMTER TRANSPORT COMPANY HAS ADDED THE REQUIREMENT THAT TWO PEOPLE CONDUCT A TANKER CHECK BEFORE TRANSPORTATION. THE FIRST EMPLOYEE PHYSICALLY CONFIRMS EACH LATCH IS SECURED, AND THE SECOND EMPLOYEE MONITORS THE FIRST EMPLOYEE. THE INSPECTION DOCUMENTATION IS THEN COMPLETED BY BOTH EMPLOYEES.

Side mounted float-type liquid level indicator leaked from stuffing box where shaft passed through gland nut. Gland nut was tightened by consignee personnel. Leak stopped. Tank was inspected upon return to Carrier. Driver reported "Gauge" was leaking. Tank was pressurized and soap solution applied to all three "gauges". Top "gauge" replaced due to air bubbles coming from mounting stem.  Second identical incident occurred on 3/7/2016 except that leak (drip) from liquid level indicator didn't begin until tank was vented to facilitate unloading. Dripping material was collected in small container at consignee. Tanker was returned to carrier maintenance facility and a more accurate description of leak location was provided to shop manager. Liquid level indicator was removed and determined to be irreparable. Solid 316 stainless steel flange was welded over float level indicator mounting flange. Action Resources, Inc. maintains our "R" Stamp to perform maintenance on ASME pressure vessels (DOT 412).
column169: Require more accurate information be reported to maintenance department regarding any leaking components of trailers.

column168: TO WHOM IT CONCERNS,     I, ROBERT MCGHEE ARRIVED TO LOAD PG 64-22 AT NUSTAR ON FEB, 22, 2010 AT 10:30PM. CARDED IN AND BEGAN TO LOAD THE TRAILER 1618 WITH ASPHALT. AFTER LOADING TRAILER I SAW THAT THE ASPHALT WAS REACTING TO THE WATER ON THE LAST PRODUCT HAULED ON THE TRAILER.     I REMOVED THE SPOUT AND LET TRAILER SIT FOR ABOUT TWENTY MINUTES AND THEN PROCEEDED TO MOVE TRUCK AND TRAILER OFF THE SCALE. ONCE OFF THE SCALE THE PRODUCT STARTED REACTING VIOLENTLY AND THAT’S WHEN I CALLED THE PLANT’S OPERATOR, MY DISPATCHER, AND INSURANCE COMPANY. THIS HAPPENED AROUND 11:15 PM.

column43: RECYCLABLE MATERIAL FOR PRECIOUS METAL RECOVERY
column168: THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT TWO BINS HAD SPILLED THE MATERIAL. THE TWO BOLTS/RODS THAT PUT TENSION ON THE BOTTOM OUTLET PLATE HAD LOOSENED CAUSING A GAP BETWEEN THE PLATE AND BOTTOM OF THE HOPPER. THE RESPONSE TEAM LIGHTED THE RODS TO SECURE THE PLATE TO THE HOPPER PROPERLY. THE RELEASE COULD HAVE BEEN CAUSED BECAUSE THE RODS WERE NOT TIGHTENED IN THE FIRST PLACE, OR BECAUSE IT COULD BE A DESIGN FLAW AND HAD LOOSENED OVER TIME DURING TRANSPORTATION. THE SOLID MATERIAL THAT WAS RELEASED WAS CONTAINERIZED AND PLACED INTO A DOT METAL 55 GALLON OPEN TOP DRUM. THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINED ONLY TO THE TRAILER AND NOT ON THE GROUND.
column169: THESE FLOW BINS NEED TO BE INSPECTED TO ENSURE THAT THE CLOSURE DEVICE IS PROPERLY WORKING AND PROVIDING THE PROPER PRESSURE. TRAINING MAY NEED TO BE COMPLETED TO ENSURE THAT PERSONNEL KNOW HOW TO SECURELY CLOSE THE FLOW BIN CLOSURE.

At 0715 EST dock personnel with R&L Carriers (KAN) terminal contacted ERTS regarding a release. Travis reported that (1) 55 gallon drum of UN3082 Class 9 PG III Environmentally Hazardous Substance, Liquid, n.o.s., trade name EverGLIDE UV 691 was found leaking on the concrete terminal dock. An estimated .25 gallons of material has impacted the terminal dock. The spill was reported to have been contained at this time. The cause of the release was reported to be unknown. No soils, waterways, or drains ere reported to have been impacted by the release.

During unloading activities, one 1 gallon container of UN1903 Disinfectant was discovered to be crushed by freight stacked on top resulting in approximately 0.5 liquid gallons to be released to the cardboard packaging. No material released outside the cardboard. Terminal employees placed the damaged container and packaging into a 5 gallon recovery drum to be staged onsite pending disposition. No drains, soils, or waterways were impacted.

During unloading activities, one 1 gallon plastic jug containing UN2924 "Care Catalyst Low VOC" was discovered leaking form an apparent defective seam releasing approximately 4 liquid ounces to the cardboard box and trailer floor. Onsite personnel conducted clean up procedures and placed all impacted materials into a poly lined recovery drum to be staged onsite pending disposition. No drains, soils, or waterways were impacted.

column168: EMPLOYEE WAS UNLOADING SODIUM HYDROXIDE 50% SOLUTION FROM A RAIL CAR INTO A MOTOR VEHICLE TRAILER TANKER AT THE TRANS LOAD FACILITY OPERATED BY QUALITY CARRIERS, INC. THE EMPLOYEE DID NOT INSPECT THE DISCHARGE VALVE ON THE TANKER BEFORE INITIATING THE TRANSFER AND THE VALVE WAS OPEN. UPON INITIATING TRANSFERRING, THE EMPLOYEE NOTICED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS BEING RELEASED FROM THE TANKER AS IT WAS ENTERING. HE IMMEDIATELY STOPPED THE TRANSFER AND CLOSED THE DISCHARGE VALVE ON THE TANKER. APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS WAS SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND BELOW THE TANKER. THE SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION IMPACTED AN AREA CONSISTING OF GRAVEL/BASE ROCK MATERIAL.       ALLIED INTERNATIONAL EMERGENCY (AIE) EXCAVATED APPROXIMATELY 15 CUBIC YARDS OF IMPACTED GRAVEL/SOIL FROM THE SPILL AREA. THEY PLACED THE MATERIAL INTO A ROLL-OFF CONTAINER FOR FURTHER DISPOSAL PENDING PROFILE APPROVAL.
column169: ADDITIONAL TRAINING IS REQUIRED TO PREVENT RECURRENCE OF THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT. EMPLOYEES SHOULD BE THOROUGHLY TRAINED AS TO THE PROPER INSPECTIONS REQUIRED DURING TRANS-LOADING ACTIVITIES.

column168: While car was in the "bowl" in the Barstow yard, local Carmen noticed a strong smell emitting from EAMX 25500. Upon notification to BNSF HazMat responder, the responder identified the car as EAMX 25500. BNSF responder climbed car to notice three manway bolts less than tool tight. Manway was opened to discover a badly deteriorated gasket. The gasket was removed and scraped clean from the manway and a new gasket was installed onto the nozzle. The manway was reclosed and all bolts tightened tool-tight in the proper sequence.    Q19 (Quantity Released): The vapor release quantity is an estimation.
column169: Shipper should ensure proper securement of the manway bolts to tool-tight. Shipper should also inspect the manway gasket for damage prior to shipping every load. Replace the manway gasket as necessary. Ensure all other aspects of the rail car are secure prior to shipping to prevent the release of hazardous materials in the future.

column168: ON FEBRUARY 11 AT APPROXIMATELY 8 PM AT THE MINI MART SHEET #659 DRIVER BRAD LINDSEY WAS UNLOADING GAS AND HAD A SPILL. MR. LINDSEY FAILED TO ENSURE THAT THE UNDERGROUND TANKS WOULD HOLD THE LOAD BEING DELIVERED. WHILE HE WAS DROPPING THE GAS THE OVERFILL PROTECTION DEVICE (AKA FLAPPER VALVE) FAILED RESULTING IN THE SPILLAGE OF ROUGHLY 950 GALLONS OF GASOLINE. THE MAJORITY OF THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED ON THE PAVED PORTION OF THE PARKING LOT BUT A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT DID GO INTO THE NEARBY STORM DRAIN. ECO TECH OUT OF LONDON KY WAS CALLED FOR REMEDIATION. ECO TECH CONTINUES TO MONITOR THE SPILL WELLS ON CONTAMINATED SURROUNDING AREAS FOR RESIDUAL PRODUCT.
column169: THE RESPONSIBLE DRIVER (BRAD LINDSEY) EMPLOYMENT WITH BARGER LEASING, INC HAS BEEN TERMINATED. THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANKS AT THE MINI MART #659 HAVE BEEN TESTED AND ALL NECESSARY REPAIRS WILL BE OR HAVE ALREADY BEEN MADE

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: THE EXACT CAUSE OF THE RELEASE IS NOT KNOWN FOR SURE. THE SHIPMENT WAS LOADED ONTO A 53' DRY VAN TRAILER (531572) AT THE LME TERMINAL IN FARGO, ND AND WAS ONE OF THE LAST ORDERS PUT ON THE TRAILER. THERE WERE NO SIGNS OF ANYTHING BEING DAMAGED OR LEAKING NOR WAS THERE AN ODOR PRESENT. TRAILER DOOR WAS CLOSED AND TRAILER DOOR WAS CLOSED AND TRAILER SEALED FOR BISMARCK, ND. THE TRIP FROM FARGO TO BISMARCK IS APPROXIMATELY 4 HOURS. THE DRIVE WAS STOPPED FOR APPROXIMATELY ONE HOUR DUE TO FLAT TIRE. THE DRIVER DID NOT NOTICE ANYTHING LEAKING OUT OF THE TRAILER OR SMELLING ANYTHING UNUSUAL. TRAILER REMAINED SEALED AND DRIVER CONTINUED THE RUN AFTER TIRE WAS CHANGED. UPON ARRIVAL IN BISMARCK, ND A DOCKWORKER STARTED TO UNLOAD THE TRAILER AND DISCOVERED THE DAMAGED DRUM AND NOTIFIED THEIR SUPERVISOR. THE SUPERVISOR INSPECTED THE DRUM AND DETERMINED THE DRUM WAS EMPTY. THERE WAS EVIDENCE THAT THE PRODUCT LEAKED ONTO THE WOOD PALLET. IT APPEARED THAT THE WOOD PALLET AND A COUPLE OF SURROUNDING WOODS PALLETS ALONG WITH THE WOOD FLOOR OF THE TRAILER ABSORBED THE PRODUCT. THERE WAS NO LIQUID PRESENT TO CLEAN UP.     IN INTERVIEWING THE LOCAL TERMINAL MANGER, IT IS HIM OPINION THAT THEY LIKELY CAUSE WAS THE LOADER DID NOT PROPERLY LOAD THE SKID OF DRUMS BY GOING IN PART WAY, SETTING DOWN THE PALLET, PULLING BACK THE FORKS AND PUSHING THE PALLET UP INTO PLACE. IN NOT FOLLOWING PROPER LOADING PROCEDURES, ONE FORK MAY HAVE COMPROMISED THE DRUM.    SDS WERE OBTAINED AND SENT TO ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT, INC. IT WAS NOT NECESSARY TO DISPATCH A CLEANUP CREW TO THE SITE BECAUSE THERE WAS NOTHING REMAINING TO CLEAN UP.
column169: LME VALUES THEIR EMPLOYEES AND THE PUBLIC AND WILL CONTINUE TO STRIVE TO DO ITS BEST TO ENSURE THE SAFETY OF EVERYONE. SAFE WORK PROCEDURES MUST BE FOLLOWED TO PREVENT DAMAGE, SPILLS AND INJURIES.     ALL DOCKWORKERS AND DRIVERS HAVE RECEIVED REMEDIAL TRAINING IN THE PROPER LOADING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the transfer operation, it was discovered that one container was missing a bung.   The driver then tried to over-pack the container which resulted in it dropping and spilling 0.5 gallons.  Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place the compromised  container into a suitable salvage drum. In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and  placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, the driver did not notice the missing bung.  Drivers will continue to inspect each container during staging period as well as before it is loaded and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity and / or missing pieces.     One driver was retrained on drum integrity.  The second driver was terminated.                             IN addition, the shipper has been advised of the situation and has been asked to inspect all container used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required specifications.

column168: PROX 92157 was noted to be a slight "hissing" during an inspection.  Upon further inspection of issue, the hissing was noted as coming from the liquid valve plug on the "A" end of the car. A smell of mercaptan was also noted in the immediate area of the plug.  The liquid valve was tightened further by hand and the leak seemed to have stopped. At this time, the plug on this same liquid valve was noted to have no sealant or Teflon tape applied to it, but was tool tight.    The contractor arrived on scene and performed a further evaluation.  The contractor was able to tighten the valve further.  It was noted that it seemed like the liquid valve was loosening on its own.  It was determined that the packing was loose on the valve and the contractor tightened the packing gland nut, stopping the leak.  The liquid valve plug was removed, cleaned, and wrapped with Teflon tape prior to be reinstalled and tool tightened.  The valve in question, along with the other valves were all leak tested with Snoop and no further issues were noted.    Note: Question #19 is an estimation of vapor release from the container.
column169: Shipper should ensure proper securement of the valves and all other aspects of the rail car prior to shipping to prevent the release of hazardous materials in the future. Leak testing and proper maintenance of valves must be completed prior to moving any shipments. Proper sealing of valve plugs with liquid sealant or Teflon tape should be utilized for all shipments prior to movement.

column168: Car UTLX 208941 was noted to be leaking from the bottom outlet valve at rate of 2 drips per minute.  Minimal amount noted on ground due to evaporation.  Contractor arrived  and noted that BOV cap was less than tool tight and missing any type of sealant. BOV was closed at time.  BOV cap was removed and any residual product was contained.  The threads were cleaned and Teflon tape applied.  BOV cap was reapplied tool tight and no further leaks were noted.    Manway was opened to find approx. 10 gallons of product remaining.  No seal was found on combination housing lid.  New seal applied #615580    Los Angeles County fire department HazMat coordinator also responded to scene to investigate situation. No other FD units responded.
column169: Shipper should ensure proper securement of the valves and all other aspects of the rail car prior to shipping to prevent the release of hazardous materials in the future.  All caps/plugs must have sealant or Teflon tape applied to them prior to movement of car to ensure no product leakage. All plugs or caps MUST be tool tight.

column162: DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS + ER
column168: The SHPX 204767 was found on February 25th, 2016 to be leaking vapor as indicated by an odor and possible visual wetness around the vapor valve by Mr. Raymond Hubbell (ODOT Rail Hazmat Inspector).  The car was inspected by BNSF Hazmat Responder and setout to a repair track.  On 2/26/16, a BNSF Hazmat contractor arrived to perform repairs on the car.  During the inspection, it was found that two of four liquid line flange bolts were loose, a small amount of vapor was being released between the liquid line flange and gasket.  These bolts were tightened by approximately 2 full turns.  The vapor line was also removed to clean, inspect and reapply thread tape to the connection.  All other closures and fittings were inspected.  The car was held pending the shipper obtaining an FRA OTMA for movement to destination for offloading and to home shop for repair.  The OTMA-3 was obtained on March 4th, 2016 and the car was released to continue on.  The estimated release amount has been estimated based up information obtained from responders and inspectors.
column169: Redfield Energy was contacted and provided details regarding the findings and situation with the SHPX 204767.  Specifically, the shipper should ensure proper securement of cars and ensure that their procedures are applicable to identify issues such as this.  All fittings and closures should be thoroughly inspected and must be in tool-tight condition prior to offering for transportation.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the offloading  operation, it was discovered that approximately one pint of liquid had escaped from a crack that had developed at the top of one tote.   Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to take the product from the compromised tote into two new totes.  In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used were collected and  placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was observed. Drivers will continue to inspect each container during staging period as well as before it is loaded and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity. IN addition, the shipper has been advised of the situation and have been asked to inspect all container used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required  specifications.

ON FEB 2ND, 2016 AT 9:15 AM, MR. ERIK LEWIS (A DRIVER EMPLOYED BY SOUTHEASTERN FUEL TRANSPORT) WAS UNLOADING DIESEL FUEL FROM HIS TANKER INTO THE TANK AT 78 VAN HORNE ST, TYBEE ISLAND, GA. THE HOSE CONNECTION FAILED AND THE DIESEL BEGAN TO FLOW ON THE GROUND BEFORE THE DRIVER HAD A CHANCE TO PUSH THE SHUT OFF VALVE. 15 GALLONS OF DIESEL RAN THROUGH THE PARKING LOT AND INTO THE STORM DRAIN, SWS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES ARRIVED AT 11:00 AM TO CLEAN, CONTAIN AND REMOVE THE DIESEL. THERE IS NOT ACUTE OR CHRONIC HEALTH RISK AND NO EVACUATIONS WERE NECESSARY.
column169: IMPRESSED ON ALL DRIVERS TO CHECK HOSE CONNECTION BEFORE LEAVING THE YARD

column168: ON FEBRUARY 21, 2016, AT APPROXIMATELY 12:30 PM CST, A TANKER TRUCK OPERATED BY CTL TRANSPORTATION, LLC (CTL) WAS STOPPED AT A WEIGH STATION ON SOUTHBOUND I-95 NEAR PALM COAST, FLORIDA. WHEN FLORIDA HIGHWAY PATROL RECOGNIZED AN ODOR COMING FROM THE TANKER. UPON INSPECTION, A SMALL LEAK WAS OBSERVED ON THE UNDERSIDE OF THE TANK FROM A PREVIOUS REPAIR. AS A RESULT, A MINIMAL AMOUNT OF MINERAL SPIRITS WERE RELEASED FROM THE TANK TO THE OUTER SEHLL OFF THE TANK SURFACE.   AT APPROXIMATELY 1:09 P.M/ CST, MS. SU MELCHIORRE OF CTL RETAINED CURE EMERGENCY SERVICE, LC (CES) TO MANAGE THE ENVIRONMENTAL ASSESSMENT OF THE SITE. THE CES INCIDENT MANAGER CONTACTED THE DRIVER OF THE UNIT. MR. DAVID LOPEZ, TO GAIN ADDITIONAL INFORMATION. MR. LOPEZ ADVISED CES OF THE CURRENT SITE CONDITIONS. BASED ON THE AVAILABLE INFORMATION, THE CES INCIDENT MANAGER DISPATCHED A CREW FROM HULL'S ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (HES) TO ASSESS TO THE SITE AND INITIATE ANY CORRECTIVE ACTIONS. THE INCIDENT MANAGER ADVISED CTL PERSONNEL AS TO THE ESTIMATED TIME OF ARRIVAL FOR THE RESPONSE CREW.    THE CREW FROM HES MOBILIZED TO THE SITE AND MET WITH MR. LOPEZ. THE LEAKING AREA WAS ASSESSED AND WIPED CLEAN WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL. NO PRODUCT WAS OBSERVED ON THE ASPHALT SURFACE OF THE WEIGHT STATION. BASED ON THE ASSESSMENT OF THE RESPONSE CREW AND CTL PERSONNEL. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE TANK MAY REQUIRE IMMEDIATE OR SUBSEQUENT REPAIR DUE TO THE QUESTIONABLE CARGO TANK INTEGRITY. UPON COMPLETION OF THE ASSESSMENT, HES PERSONNEL DEMOBILIZED FROM THE SITE.    CTL PERSONNEL ENLISTED ANOTHER TANKER TRUCK TO THE SITE AND COMPLETED A TRANSFER OF THE FLUID.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. ROLL-OVER ACCIDENT RESULTING IN RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 200 GALLONS FROM THREE DOME LIDS. THE FREE LIQUID IMPACTED SOIL. ENVIRONMENTAL RESTORATION, LLC TRANSFERRED THE PRODUCT FROM THE TANKER INTO A RESCUE TANKER AND EXCAVATED THE CONTAMINATED SOIL. ENVIRONMENTAL RESTORATION, LLC COORDINATED DISPOSAL OF THE WASTE GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT.
column169: SINCE THE RELEASE WAS ACCIDENTAL, NO PLANS CURRENTLY EXIST TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. HOWEVER, REPUBLIC CARRIERS, LLC WILL CONTINUE TO REINFORCE SAFETY GUIDELINES AND HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column168: THERE WAS NO PACKAGE FAILURE CARGO TANK WAS OVERFILLED. DRIVER BACKED UNDER THE FERROUS CHLORIDE LOADING RACK, PLACED THE PRODUCT HOSE AND SCRUBBER LINE INTO THE TRAILER AND SECURED BOTH WITH A BUNGEE CORD. HE THEN OPENED THE PRODUCT VALVE AND TURNED ON THE PUMP AT THE TOP OF THE RACK. AS PRODUCT BEGAN TO FLOW HE REMAINED AT THE TOP OF RACK TO CONFIRM HOSES WHERE SECURE AS THE PUMP BEGAN. AFTERWARDS HE CAME DOWN FORM THE PLATFORM AND USED THE RESTROOM INSIDE THE BUILDING. WHEN HE RETURNED TO THE TRAILER HE CHECKED THE PRODUCT LEVEL INSIDE, IT APPEARED TO BE ABOUT A 1/4 TO 1/2 FULL. HE THEN WENT INTO THE CAB OF HIS TRACTOR TO SORT OUT THE PAPERWORK HE WOULD HAVE TO TURN INTO THE GUARD UPON LEAVING USX. INSIDE THE CAB HE CONTINUED TO MONITOR THE SUSPENSION LOAD GAUGE. THE GAUGE WAS READING 60 WHEN HE DEPARTED THE TRACTOR. THE GAUGE NORMALLY REACHES AROUND 70 - 80 BEFORE THE DRIVER RETURNS TO THE TOP OF THE LOADING RACK TO MONITOR THE REMAINDER OF THE LOADING. WHEN HE STEPPED DOWN OUT OF THE TRACTOR HE OBSERVED PRODUCT SPILL FROM THE DOME OF THE TRAILER. HE IMMEDIATELY RAN TO THE TOP OF THE LOADING RACK SHUTTING OFF THE PIMP AND CLOSING THE VALVES TO STOP THE PRODUCT FLOW. HE NEXT BEGAN RINSING DOWN THE TRAILER FROM THE RACK. AN EQ CREW ON SITE WORKING IN THE SAME AREA BEGAN DIKING THE AREA WITH ABSORBENT SOCKS TO CONTAIN THE SPILLED MATERIAL. USX PERSONAL ARRIVED AND JOE WAS TAKING WITH THE ER PERSONNEL TO GIVE HIS REPORT OF THE INCIDENT. WHEN HE RETURNED TO THE INCIDENT SCENE HE WAS ASKED TO MOVE THE EQUIPMENT FORM THE LOADING AREA. WHILE MOVING THE TRACTOR TRAILER OFF THE LOADING PAD AS THE TRAILER BECOMES LEVEL, RINSED DOWN MATERIAL ACCUMULATED IN THE HOSE TRAY LEAKED ONTO THE GROUND. USX ENVIRONMENTAL PERSONAL YELLED FOR THE TRUCK TO STOPPED AS THE MATERIAL LEAKING WAS OUTSIDE THE AREA OF THE SPILL. THE DRIVER STOPPED  THE TRUCK AND EXITING USED AN ABSORBENT PAD TO PLUG THE DRAIN HOLE IN THE HOSE TRAY, WITHOUT PROTECTIVE GLOVES. AFTER PLUGGING THE DRAIN HOLD HE RINSED HIS HANDS IN A NEARBY SAFETY SHOWER. THE EQ CREW APPLIED ABSORBENT SOCKS AND PADS TO THE AREA OF AND CLEANED UP THE TRAILING SPILL.
column169: THE DRIVER SHOULD REMAIN ON THE LOADING RACK OBSERVING THE LOADING DURING THE ENTIRE PROCESS. REVIEW CURRENT LOADING PROCEDURES AT TERMINAL AND DEVELOP A MODIFY FOR LOADING AT CUSTOMERS LOCATION.

THE 30 GALS OF FUEL OIL WERE CLEANED BY A REMEDIATION COMPANY AND THE TRUCK WAS CLEANED OF ALL SPILLAGE. THE TRAINEE LEARNED A VALUABLE LESSON AND HAS GONE ON TO BECOME A TRAINED HAZ MAT DRIVER.

column168: DRIVER OPERATING A TANK TRUCK/FULL TRAILER COMBINATION SWERVED TO AVOID DOG IN ROADWAY. THE TRAILER LEFT THE PAVEMENT AND ROLLED AS THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO RETURN TO HIS LANE. THE PINTLE LATCH AND THE SAFETY CABLES BOTH FAILED FROM THE TORQUE APPLIED BY THE ROLLING TRAILER, ALLOWING THE TRAILER TO BREAK LOOSE FROM THE TRUCK. THE TRAILER CAME TO A REST ON ITS SIDE, AND ONE MANWAY COVER POPPED OPEN AND ONE LEAKED PAST, RESULTING IN THE LOSS OF APPROXIMATELY 1687 GALLONS OF DENATURED ETHANOL. THE TRUCK REMAINED UPRIGHT. THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS PUMPED FROM THE TRAILER AND DELIVERED TO THE CUSTOMER. SORBENTS WERE USED TO LIMIT THE SPREAD OF THE PRODUCT. THE AFFECTED SOIL WAS EXCAVATED, WITH DISPOSAL OCCURRING, AFTER CHARACTERIZATION AND LICENSING, AT THE GALLATIN COUNTY LANDFILL IN LOGAN, MT.
column169: THE DRIVER WAS TERMINATED FOR NOT FOLLOWING COMPANY POLICY. IN DRIVER MEETINGS, WE HAVE REINFORCED TO OUR DRIVERS THE IMPORTANCE OF NOT MAKING SHARP MANEUVERS TO AVOID ANIMALS, EVEN THOUGH THAT FREQUENTLY MEANS COLLIDING WITH THE ANIMAL. WE HAVE USED THE VIDEO FROM THE ON-BOARD CAMERA TO SHOW SEVERAL CHOICES THE DRIVER MADE THAT CONTRIBUTED TO THE ROLLOVER.

column168: 2/24/2016 11:30 AM    DRIVER WAS DELIVERING DIESEL AT THE RACETRACK AT 2000 HWY 43 PICAYUNE, MS 39466. DURING THE DELIVERY, ONE OF THE CONNECTORS AT THE END OF THE DELIVERY HOSE HAD A CRACK IN IT, AND BROKE OFF COMPLETELY FROM THE DROP HEAD ON THE TRAILER. DRIER TURNED OF THE VALVE ON THE DROP HEAD ASAP. THERE WAS A RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS OF DSL ON THE GROUND. THE DRIVER BLOCKED UP THE STORM DRAIN WITH SPILL PADS, AND CALLED DISPATCH TO REPORT THE SPILL. NEWMAN TRANSPORT DISPATCHED A CLEANUP CREW TO THE SITE. DISPATCH AS WELL AS RACETRACK REPORTED SPILL TO MSDEQ. REPORT # WEB EOC#84958. PICAYUNE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS DISPATCHED TO STORE AS WELL. FIRE CHIEF KEITH BROWN (601-798-6513) WAS SATISFIED WITH CLEANUP BEFORE LEAVING STATION. NEWMAN TRANSPORT PUMPED OUT THE STORE DRAIN OF WATER AND DSL. NICK HATTEN FROM MSDEQ ALSO ON-SITE AND APPROVED OF ALL CLEANUP AND AIR TESTED STORM DRAIN. TEST WERE ACCEPTABLE. HE CLOSED OUT REPORT ON SPILL. PARKING LOT WAS PRESSURE WASHED BY NEWMAN TRANSPORT.

column168: ON FEB. 5, 2016 NEW ENGLAND MOTOR FREIGHT DELIVERED A SHIPMENT OF CLASS 3 CYCLOHEXANE TO FUELCELL ENERGY TORRINGTON, CT FACILITY. IT CONSISTED OF FOUR 55-GAL DRUMS SHRINK WRAPPED ON A PALLET. AFTER THE DRIVER UNLOADED THE PALLET ONTO OUR DOCK, HE REQUESTED A SIGNATURE FOR THE DELIVERY WHICH OUR RECEIVING DEPT. ACCOMMODATED. WHEN WE UNPACKED THE DRUMS FOR STORAGE IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE SHRINK WRAP HAD CONCEALED A PUNCTURE AT THE BOTTOM OF ONE OF THE DRUMS. FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE DRUM WAS EMPTY OF ALL ITS CONTENTS. TO REITERATE, THE RELEASE OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DID NOT OCCUR AT OUR FACILITY.     WE REPORTED THESE FINDINGS TO NEW ENGLAND MOTOR FREIGHT WHO HAS DENIED THAT THE RELEASE TOOK PLACE WHILE IN THEIR POSSESSION. THEY CONTEND THAT SINCE THE SHIPMENT WAS SIGNED FOR FREE AND CLEAR OF ANY DEFECTS UPON DELIVERY THAT THEY ARE NOT RESPONSIBLE FOR THE RELEASE.     WE DISAGREE WITH THIS STATEMENT SINCE THE BILL OF LADING FOR THIS SHIPMENT SHOWS A WEIGHT OF 1584 LBS, AND NOTED THE GROSS WEIGHT OF A DRUM OF CYCLOHEXANE AT FULL CAPACITY IS 386 LBS. IF YOU FACTOR IN THE WEIGHT OF A 40 LB PALLET, THE 1584 LBS DEPICTED ON THE BILL OF LADING WOULD SUGGEST THAT ALL FOUR DRUMS WERE AT FULL CAPACITY WHEN OFFERED FOR TRANSPORTATION BY SPECTRUM CHEMICALS MFG. CORP.     NEW ENGLAND MOTOR FREIGHT HAS STATED THAT THIS SHIPMENT WAS REWEIGHED AT THEIR PICK UP TERMINAL IN PLAINFIELD, NJ AT 1510 LBS. EVEN THIS WEIGHT WOULD SUGGEST THAT FOUR DRUMS WERE FULL OF MATERIAL. (WE HAVE CALCULATED THE WEIGHT OF THIS SHIPMENT MINUS THE CONTENTS OF ONE DRUM, WOULD WEIGHT APPROXIMATELY 1210 LBS). WE HAVE REPEATEDLY ASKED NEW ENGLAND MOTOR FREIGHT FOR A COPY OF THEIR REWEIGH CERTIFICATE BUT AS OF THIS DATE THEY HAVE NOT COMPILED.
column169: SINCE THIS WAS A FREIGHT COLLECT SHIPMENT TO FUELCELL ENERGY, WE HAVE TAKEN STEPS TO REPLACE NEW ENGLAND MOTOR FREIGHT AS A CARRIER OF THIS PRODUCT FROM SPECTRUM CHEMICAL MFG. CORP.

column168: Cause of accident was due to driver over correcting after leaving the roadway.  As a result of being on the soft dirt and his reaction to jerking the wheel, the trailer rolled over.  Due to the conflicting parties at the scene, including the fire department and the environmental health department, the trailer was on it's side for almost 20 hours before a tow truck was allowed to start the drilling process to pump out the fuel from the trailer. There was no breakage of the trailer itself.  As a result of the heat from the sun, approximately 12 hours into the incident, the dome lid on the top of the trailer started to experience minor leakage as a result of the fuel expanding. The fire department placed a containment container under the dome lid to catch the leaking vapors from the dome lid.  The leaking vapors did not have any contact with the environment.
column169: Drivers were trained on making sure to hold their lane position in the event that they leave their lane and to make sure that they do not over correct or make dangerous and abrupt turns, which may cause a rollover.

column168: A PORTABLE ISO CONTAINER SECURED TO A TRAILER AND CONTAINING CHLOROBENZENE WAS DELIVERED TO THE FACILITY SEVERAL DAYS PRIOR TO THE SPILL EVENT. THE CARRIER STAGED THE CONTAINER ON THE TRAILER, DETACHED THE CAB AND LEFT THE FACILITY. ON 2/27/2016, CHLOROBENZENE WAS PIMPED FOR THE ISO-CONTAINER BY KINDER MORGAN OPERATION INTO THE SHIP STOLT CAPABILITY AT DOCK 2 IN ORDER TO RINSE OUT THE VESSEL HOLDS AFTER IT HAD COMPLETED A DELIVERY OF METHYENE DIPHENYL DIISOCYANATE (MDI) TO THE TERMINAL'S SHORE TANKS. UPON COMPLETION OF THE RINSE, THE CHLOROBENZENE MIXED WITH RESIDUAL MDI WAS PUMPED BACK INTO A SECOND EMPTY ISO-CONTAINER. THE SECOND ISO-CONTAINER WAS FITTED WITH A VAPOR CONTROL LINE TO CAPTURE VAPORS CREATED BY LOADING THE ISO CONTAINER AND CONVEY THEM TO AN ACTIVATED CARBON UNIT BED FOR TREATMENT. THE VOLUME OF PRODUCT RETURNED FORM THE VESSEL WAS GREATER THAN THE AVAILABLE VOLUME IN THE ISO-CONTAINER AND THE CONTAINER OVERFILLED. PRODUCT LEAKED/VENTED THROUGH THE VAPOR CONTROL PIPING, INTO THE CARBON BED OUT THROUGH THE CARBON BED DISCHARGE PIPE AND ONTO THE SURROUND CONCRETE PAD. APPROXIMATELY 40 GALLONS OF CHLOROBENZENE (WITH RESIDUAL MDI) LEAKED ONTO THE CONCRETE BEFORE THE TRANSFER COULD BE SHUT DOWN. THE DISCHARGE LASTED APPROXIMATELY 5 MINUTES. INTERNAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM (ERT) PERSONNEL WERE DEPLOYED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT. THERE WAS NO IMPACT TO SURFACE WATER OR THE STORM SEWER.
column169: AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT THE TERMINAL HAS ADDED THE FOLLOWING CONTROLS:    -INSTALLED AN OVERFLOW PROBE WITH ALARM FOR THE ISO CONTAINER   -INSTALLED A FLOW/LIQUID DETECTOR WITH ALARM IN THE CARBON BED VAPOR LINE   -TIED IN THE ABOVE ALARMS TO A MOTORIZE VALVE THAT WILL AUTOMATICALLY SHUT IN THE EVEN OF AN ALARM PREVENTING FLOW TO THE CARBON BED.   -TIED IN THE EMERGENCY STOP BUTTON TO A MOTORIZED VALVE THAT WILL AUTOMATICALLY SHUT IN THE EVENT OF AN ALARM. PREVENTING FLOW TO THE CARBON BED.   -REVISE THE PROCEDURE FOR THIS LOADING ACTIVITY TO ADDRESS THE POTENTIAL FOR ISO CONTAINER OVERFILL AND THE OPERATOR AND DOCK PERSON IN CHARGE ACTIONS NECESSARY TO MITIGATE THIS SCENARIO.

column168: WHILE THE SHIPMENT WAS PARKED IN THE GRAVEL LOT WAITING TO BE OFFLOADED, A GAR EMPLOYEE NOTICED A PUDDLE OF RED COLORED LIQUID FORMING UNDER THE TRUCK. INSPECTION SHOWED THE LIQUID WAS COMING FROM THE TRAILER, SO THE TRUCK WAS IMMEDIATELY TAKEN TO THE LOADING DOCK WHERE THE DRUMS WERE OFFLOADED INTO THE CONTAINER STORAGE BUILDING. THE PUDDLE OF AN ESTIMATED 10 GALLONS (80LB) WAS ABSORBED WITH SAWDUST AND MINOR DRIPS IN THE PARKING LOT WERE SCRAPED UP AS WELL, AND APPROXIMATELY 1000LB OF CLEANUP MATERIAL WAS REMOVED TO CONTAINMENT FOR PROCESSING AS HAZARDOUS WASTE FUEL FOR THE USE IN THE CEMENT KILN. THE TRAILER WAS FOUND TO HAVE ONE LEAKING DRUM THAT HAD TWO PUNCTURES OF UNKNOWN ORIGIN. APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS REMAINED IN THE DRUM, AND THERE WAS MORE LIQUID INSIDE THE TRAILER. AFTER OFFLOADING THE TRAILER WAS MOVED TO CONTAINMENT WHERE THE LIQUID WAS ABSORBED AND REMOVED. SUBSEQUENT TO THE SPILL RESPONSE AND CLEANUP ACTIONS, A SAMPLE OF THE SPILLED SOLVENT WAS ANALYZED IN THE GAR FUELS LABORATORY. GC/MS ANALYSIS INDICATED THE PRESENCE OF BENZENE AT 9 PPM, WHICH MEANT THAT ONLY 0.00072 LB OF BENZENE WAS SPILLED. THIS IS FAR BELOW THE RQ OF 10LB. NONE OF THE OTHER CONSTITUENTS (METHANOL, ACETONE, ETHANOL, ETC) WERE OVER AN RQ. EVEN TAKING THE FULL 80 LB AMOUNT OF SOLVENT AS AN F003 OR F 005 WASTE (RQ 100LB) MEANT THAT NO RQ WAS EXCEEDED.
column169: A HIGH LEVEL MEETING OCCURRED WITH THE GENERATORS PLANT MANAGER AND OTHER SITE MANAGEMENT ON TUESDAY THE SECOND OF AUGUST 2016 ON THE LEAKING CONTAINERS. NEW PROTOCOLS WERE INSTATED FOR INSPECTIONS AT BOTH THE GENERATORS SITE AND REVIEW OF CURRENT US ENVIRONMENTAL PROCEDURE FOR LOAD INSPECTIONS. NEW PROTOCOLS WERE INSTATED FOR SEALED TRAILERS. column168: AA3475 INBOUND FROM ORD ARRIVED AT GATE 82 IN MCI AT 1144 DURING THE OFFLOAD PROCESS OF THE VALET CHECK BAGS, PIEDMONT SUPERVISOR MATT TOLLAND ENCOUNTERED A VALET BAG THAT WAS SMOKING AND HOT TO THE TOUCH. HE IMMEDIATELY CALLED ME TO ADVICE AND I RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY TO GATE 82, AND I IMMEDIATELY CALLED AIRPORT POLICE. WHILE LOOKING AT THE BAG, I NOTICED THAT THERE WAS NO NAME ON THE VALET CHECKED TAG BUT THERE WAS AN OLD BINGO STICKER FROM A PREVIOUS TRIP. I TOOK THE BINGO STICKER WENT TO THE JET WAY WHERE THE PASSENGER WERE WAITING AND CALLED OUT THE NAME ON THE BINGO STICKER, AND ONE PASSENGER CAME FORWARD. I PULLED HIM ASIDE FROM ALL THE OTHER PASSENGERS AND ASKED FOR A DESCRIPTION OF HIS VALET CHECKED BAG, AND HE GAVE ME A DESCRIPTION OF THE BAG WE HAD. I ASKED IF HE HAD ANY E-CIGARETTES OR LITHIUM BATTERIES IN HIS BAG. HE RESPONDED THAT HE HAD A GARMIN GPS UNIT IN HIS BAG. I INFORMED HIM THAT HIS BAG CAME OFF THE PLANE SMOKING HOT TO TOUCH, AND THAT WE HAD CALLED THE AIRPORT POLICE WHO NEEDED TO CLEAR THE BAG BEFORE WE COULD HAND IT OVER TO HIM. HE REPLIED THAT HE UNDERSTOOD AND I ASKED HIM TO WAIT IN THE JET WAY. WHILE I WAS WITH THE PASSENGER, MATT HAD THE RAMP AGENTS’ FLAG DOWN OFFICER SANDY THOMPSON BY GATE 82. I EXPLAINED THE SITUATION TO OFFICER THOMPSON, AND HE INSPECTED THE BAG AND ITS CONTENTS. WHILE OFFICER THOMPSON SEARCHED THE BAG, JOHN LANE, CMS CONTACTED THE TSA COORDINATION CENTER.     OFFICER THOMPSON CLEARED THE BAG AND WE WENT TO THE JET WAY FOR HIM TO QUESTION THE PASSENGER.

column168: THIS UNLABELED AND UNMARKED PLASTIC PELICAN SHIPPING CASE WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE SOMETHING LEAKING INSIDE. UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS THEY FOUND SOME LIQUOR BOTTLE THAT HAD BROKEN. ALSO INSIDE THE PACKAGE WAS A KEG OF BEER AND SEVERAL DANGEROUS GOODS ITEMS WHICH INCLUDED 1 CYLINDER OF CARBON DIOXIDE ABOUT 15 LBS 1 CYLINDER OF CARBON DIOXIDE ABOUT 4 LBS 2 NON FLAMMABLE AEROSOL CANS .456 KG AND CORROSIVE LIQUID NOS PHOSPHORIC ACID. NONE OF THE DANGEROUS GOODS ITEMS LEAKED ONLY THE LIQUOR AND THAT’S IS HOW IT WAS DISCOVERED.
